H1: Markdown to Portable Text: A Complete Guide
P: Converting markdown to Portable Text is a [strong:powerful] way to bridge the gap between [em:simple text formatting] and [strong:[em:structured content]].
H2: Why Portable Text?
P: Portable Text is a [strong:specification] for [em:rich text] that is:
UL:
  LI: Platform [strong:agnostic]
  LI: [strong:Structured] and [em:queryable]
  LI: Designed for [strong:[em:modern content workflows]]
P: Visit [@link href="https://portabletext.org":https://portabletext.org] for more information, or check out the [@link href="https://github.com/portabletext/portabletext":official documentation].
{HORIZONTAL-RULE}
H2: Supported Features
H3: Text Formatting
P: You can use [strong:bold text], [em:italic text], [code:inline code], and even [strike-through:strikethrough] text. The parser handles [strong:[em:nested formatting]] gracefully, including [strong:[em:bold and italic]] combined.
P: Here’s some [code:code with **bold inside**] and [strong:text with ][strong:[code:code inside]] to test edge cases.
H3: Links and Images
P: Reference-style links work too! Check out this [@link href="https://portabletext.org":example link] that uses references defined elsewhere.
{IMAGE alt="A beautiful diagram" src="https://example.com/diagram.png" title="Markdown to PT Flow"}
P: Here’s an inline image in text: {image alt="icon" src="https://example.com/icon.png"} followed by more text.
H3: Code Blocks
P: Fenced code blocks with syntax highlighting:
{CODE code="function markdownToPortableText(markdown) {\n  const tokens = parseMarkdown(markdown)\n  return transformToPortableText(tokens)\n}" language="javascript"}
P: Indented code blocks also work:
{CODE code="const simple = \"code block\";\nconsole.log(simple);"}
H3: Blockquotes
BLOCKQUOTE: Markdown is a lightweight markup language for creating formatted text.
BLOCKQUOTE: It was created by John Gruber in 2004.
P: Nested blockquotes are supported:
BLOCKQUOTE: This is the outer quote
BLOCKQUOTE: And this is nested deeper
BLOCKQUOTE: With multiple paragraphs
H3: Lists
H4: Unordered Lists
UL:
  LI: [strong:Bold item] in a list
  LI: [em:Italic item] with [@link href="https://example.com":a link]
  LI:
    P: Item with [code:inline code]
    UL:
      LI: Nested item one
      LI:
        P: Nested item two
        UL:
          LI: Even deeper nesting
  LI: Back to top level
H4: Ordered Lists
OL:
  LI: First step: Parse the markdown
  LI: Second step: Generate tokens
  LI:
    P: Third step: Transform to Portable Text
    OL:
      LI: Map block types
      LI: Handle inline formatting
      LI: Preserve structure
H4: Mixed Lists
OL:
  LI:
    P: Ordered parent
    UL:
      LI: Unordered child
      LI:
        P: Another unordered
        OL:
          LI: Back to ordered
          LI: Still ordered
  LI: Continue ordered parent
