H2: Advanced Examples
H3: Overlapping Formatting
P: This paragraph contains [strong:bold with ][strong:[em:italic inside]] and [em:italic with ][em:[strong:bold inside]] to test proper nesting.
P: You can also have [strong:bold with ][strong:[code:code]] and [em:italic with ][em:[code:code]] and even [code:code with **bold** and _italic_] (though the formatting inside code should be preserved as-is).
H3: Links with Formatting
P: Here’s a [strong:[@link href="https://example.com":bold link]] and an [em:[@link href="https://example.com":italic link]] and even a [code:[@link href="https://example.com":code link]].
H3: Complex List Items
UL:
  LI: Item with [strong:bold], [em:italic], and [code:code]
  LI: Item with a [@link href="https://example.com":link to ][strong:[@link href="https://example.com":bold]][@link href="https://example.com": content]
  LI:
    P: Item with an inline image {image alt="small icon" src="https://example.com/icon.png"} in the middle
    UL:
      LI: Nested [strong:bold item] with [em:italic] and [code:code]
      LI: Another nested item
H3: Line Breaks
P: This is a line with a hard break
that continues on the next line but stays in the same paragraph.
P: Another paragraph with a break
and more content.
H3: Autolinks
P: Check out these autolinks: [@link href="https://example.com":https://example.com] and [@link href="mailto:hello@example.com":mailto:hello@example.com] for quick linking.
H3: HTML Passthrough
{HTML html="<div class=\"custom-block\">\n  <p>This is raw HTML that gets preserved</p>\n</div>"}
P: Inline HTML like highlighted text can be handled too.
H3: Reference Links
P: This is [@link href="https://portabletext.org":reference link one] and this is [@link href="https://github.com/portabletext/editor":reference link two].
P: You can also use [@link href="https://example.com":implicit references] by just using the text as the reference.
H2: Implementation Notes
P: The transformation process involves several key steps:
OL:
  LI: [strong:Lexical Analysis]: Parse markdown into tokens
  LI: [strong:Syntax Tree Building]: Construct an AST from tokens
  LI: [strong:Transformation]: Map markdown AST to Portable Text structure
  LI: [strong:Validation]: Ensure output conforms to schema
H3: Edge Cases
H4: Empty Blocks
P: Sometimes you have empty paragraphs:
P: Or consecutive horizontal rules:
{HORIZONTAL-RULE}
{HORIZONTAL-RULE}
H4: Special Characters
P: Text with special characters like [code:&amp\;], [code:&lt\;], and [code:&gt\;] should be handled correctly.
H4: URLs in Text
P: Raw URLs like [@link href="https://example.com":https://example.com] (without angle brackets) may or may not become links depending on the parser configuration.
H2: Conclusion
P: This document demonstrates the [strong:comprehensive] support for [em:markdown features] in the [code:markdown-to-portable-text] converter. With proper handling of:
UL:
  LI: All basic formatting
  LI: Complex nesting
  LI: Various link types
  LI: Images (block and inline)
  LI: Code blocks
  LI: Lists of all types
  LI: Tables
  LI: And much more!
P: The result is [strong:[em:robust, reliable]] content transformation that preserves both structure and semantics.
{HORIZONTAL-RULE}
P: [strong:Happy converting!] 🎉
P: [em:Last updated: 2025]